===Etymology 3===
From the phonetic similarity between {{m|en|our}} and {{m|en|are}} in many English dialects (both {{IPAchar|/ɑː(ɹ)/}}).

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ɑː(ɹ)/|a=UK}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)|s=1}}

====Determiner====
{{head|en|misspelling}}

# {{lb|en|UK|US}} {{misspelling of|en|our}}.

=====Usage notes=====
Sometimes used deliberately as a form of [[classist]] humour, as a mocking imitation of a person with little education.

